    <text>
        <body><div type="bibliography">
                
                <p>Never published before this edition.</p>
            </div><div type="edition" xml:lang="grc" xml:space="preserve">
                
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/><persName type="attested" key=""><name><unclear>Φ</unclear>ιλύ<supplied reason="lost">τας</supplied></name></persName> <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/><certainty locus="name" match=".."/>
                    <lb n="2"/><persName type="attested" key=""><name>Εὖφρ<unclear>ι</unclear><supplied reason="lost">ς</supplied></name></persName> <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/><certainty locus="name" match=".."/>
                </ab>
            </div><div type="apparatus" xml:space="preserve">
            
                <p/>
               </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="fr">
            <p>Philytas <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/> Euphris <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/>.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="en">
           <p>Philytas <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/> Euphris <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/>.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="it">
           <p>Philytas <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/> Euphris <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/>.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="ar">
            <p/>
         </div><div type="commentary">
                
             <p>The shape of the stone, an oblong panel, lets us suppose that each line contained more than one name. Furthermore, line 2 has letters not really different in style, but a bit smaller 
             than at line 1. Each line thus contained probably a name followed by the related father's name. Anyhow, both lines were probably cut by the same hand, exluding the hypothesis of a list of priests,
             an idea which would also be discarded by the type of support.</p>
             <p>Generally speaking, the name <foreign xml:lang="grc">Φιλύτας</foreign> is rather rare, but it is more frequent at Cyrene, one occurrence near in date being in <ref type="inscription" source="#IGCyr2">IGCyr104000</ref>. A very small 
                 vestige of hasta above the break at line 2 allows to exclude an alpha and to read an iota, whence the name <foreign xml:lang="grc">Εὖφρις</foreign> rather than <foreign xml:lang="grc">Εὐφράνωρ</foreign>, both the compound form and the shorter one being typical in Cyrenaica. </p>
            </div></body>
    </text>
